\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 When you type "https://www.google.com" into your browser and press Enter, a series of events take place in order to display the webpage on your screen. Let's break it down step by step.\
\
DNS Request:\
The first thing that happens is a Domain Name System (DNS) request is sent out. DNS is like a phone book for the internet. It converts the domain name (www.google.com) into an IP address (216.58.194.174), which is the actual address where the website resides. Your browser sends a request to your ISP's DNS server to find the IP address of www.google.com.\
\
TCP/IP:\
Once your browser has the IP address, it initiates a Transmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol (TCP/IP) connection to the server at that IP address. TCP/IP is the set of communication protocols used to connect devices on the internet. It breaks the data down into packets, and these packets are sent and received between your computer and the server.\
\
Firewall:\
Before any data is exchanged, the server's firewall checks to make sure that the request is legitimate and not malicious. A firewall is a network security system that monitors and controls incoming and outgoing network traffic based on predetermined security rules.\
\
HTTPS/SSL:\
