Load-balancer:\
If there are multiple servers available to handle the request, a load-balancer will distribute the request across these servers to ensure that the load is balanced and no single server becomes overloaded. A load-balancer is a device that evenly distributes network traffic across multiple servers.\
\
Web server:\
Once the request has been received by the server, it is passed to the web server, which is responsible for handling HTTP requests. The web server will locate the requested resource, which in this case is the Google homepage, and return it to the browser as an HTTP response.\
\
Application server:\
If the request requires data from a database or other back-end system, the web server will send the request to an application server, which will handle the request and provide the necessary data. An application server is a server that is dedicated to running specific applications or services.\
\
Database:\
If the request requires data from a database, the application server will connect to the database and retrieve the necessary data. The database is a repository for data that can be queried and manipulated by other applications or services.\
In conclusion, when you type "https://www.google.com" into your browser and press Enter, a complex series of events takes place to retrieve and display the webpage. The DNS request, TCP/IP connection, firewall, HTTPS/SSL encryption, load-balancer, web server, application server, and database all work together seamlessly to deliver the requested resource to your browser.}